Assessing the Probability of the St.Louis Blues Winning the Stanley Cup

Three Simulations based on Constant Elo Team Ratings MATH2223 - Sports Analytics Course Project

Ben Cole - s3412349

Abstract

The St.Louis Blues won the National Hockey Leagues Stanley Cup at the end of the 2018-19 season, crowning them champions for the first time in their NHL history. The below paper examines the change in St.Louis Blues performance throughout the season by simulating the remainder of the season and finals playoffs from two demarcations in the data and using the results from the entire season. Constant Elo ratings were calculated for each partition in the data set and Monte Carlo models were built around these Elo ratings to simulate all games occurring after the partition. The simulations highlighted the extent of the turn around in the season for the St.Louis Blues, but still showed that their chances of winning the Stanley Cup at the end of the regular season were comparatively slim. This study could have been improved by changing the method used to partition the data, by changing how season standings were calculated, and providing further granularity to the simulations.

1 Introduction

The National Hockey League (hereon NHL) is the North American ice hockey competition held each year across the winter months of the Northern hemisphere. The regular season begins in October and usually ends in April the following year, with the finals playoffs series culminating in the competition for the coveted Stanley Cup usually in June. (NHL, 2019)

1.1 St.Louis Blues - Underdogs

The St.Louis Blues were the winners of the 2018-2019 Stanley Cup playoffs, winning a 4-3 series against the Boston Bruins. The Blues winning the Stanley Cup was paticularly extraordinary not only because it was the first in their history as a club in the NHL, but also because they faced off against the Bruins who have appeared so regularly in the Stanley Cup Playoffs. Since joining the NHL in 1967, the St Louis Blues have contested the Stanley Cup Playoffs only 4 times, whilst the Boston Bruins have made it to the Cup Playoffs 10 times since 1967 (and a total 20 since joining the NHL in 1924). (NHL, 2019)

What arguably made the St.Louis Blues appearance in the Stanley Cup Finals most incredible was that they ranked last in January of the same season. Sometime between January and April they managed to claw their way to clinching a playoffs appearance. (Bardown, 2019)

1.2 NHL Season and Post-Season Structure

The NHL contained a total of 31 teams in the 2019 season. These 31 teams were split across two conferences, Eastern and Western. The conferences comprised two divisions each; Metropolitan and Atlantic in the Eastern Conference and Central and Pacific in the Western Conference. (NHL, 2019)

Throughout the regular season each team played 82 games, which were a mixture of home and away fixtures. As the playing season was approximately 27 weeks, these 82 games averaged out to be more than three games per week. Therefore, unlike many Australian sporting codes, there were no rounds in the NHL but simply game numbers. Further, there is no structure or restriction to which game each team is playing. For example, one team may be playing their 26th game against an opponent that is playing their 23rd. (NHL, 2019)
If a team won a game in the regular season they were awarded 2 points for the win. If the game had a tied scoreline at the end of the third 20-minute period it went into overtime. If the scoreline was still tied at the end of two overtime periods then a shootout was played until a winner was decided. The team that won by any method, including overtime or shootout, was awarded 2 points towards their season standings. A team that lost in overtime or shootout was awarded one point. If the game was decided before overtime the losing team was awarded 0 points. (MacDonald, R, 2018)

Points awarded for different win types in NHL regular season

Overtime or Shootout 2 1

Once the regular season finished and team standings had been calculated, a bracketed finals system was drawn up for the playoffs. The finals playoffs followed a repeating knockout structure that has 3 rounds before reaching the Stanley Cup playoffs. Each conference follows the same structure, so only one will be described as follows:

1.2.1 Playoffs Selection

A total of 16 teams from both conferences qualify for the finals playoffs. The top three teams in each division are awarded spots in the playoffs. As there are two divisions in each conference, this results in 6 teams in each conference making it to the finals. A further two spots are awarded to the next two highest ranking teams in the conference that did not make the playoffs. As this is based on standings in the conference overall, its possible for a division to send two wildcards through to the playoffs.

1.2.1.1 First Round

In the first round the highest-ranked division winner plays the lowest-ranked wildcard entrant. The lesser-ranked division winner then plays the remaining wildcard entrant. Teams ranked second and third within each division play each other. Each pairing is decided by a series of games which is decided when one team wins 4 times. This results in a series length that can be anywhere between 4 (winning 4-0) and 7 (winning 4-3), or the best of 7 games.

1.2.1.2 Second Round

The winners of each of each First Round series then play each other in the second round, keeping within divisions and ignoring wildcards. Again, a best of 7 series is played in each pairing.

1.2.1.3 Conference Round

The winners of each Second Round series face off in the Conference round, which decides the winner of each conference via a best of 7 games series.

1.2.1.4 Stanley Cup

The winners of each Conference Round series play off in the Stanley Cup finals, which are also a best of 7 series.

As it happened: The 2018-2019 Finals Playoffs Series. Source: https://www.nhl.com/stanley-cup-playoffs

2 Aim

2.1 Research Question

Considering the turn around in the St.Louis Blues performance within the season and the lengthy multiple finals series, what were the chances that the St.Louis Blues could win the Stanley Cup from their standings at the end of the regular season? Further, did this chance change considerably from their standings at the end of their 25th and 50th games?

2.2 Overview of Methods

To answer the above questions, Monte Carlo simulations were performed to simulate the season based on Elo ratings at different points in time. These partitions in the data were set at 25 games, 50 games, and the end of the regular season of 82 games.

3 Literature Review

3.1 Elo Rating Models

3.1.1 Predictive Model Overview

Elo Models have a long history for rating teams and players in sport. The first application for Elo models was in rating chess players as applied in the text The rating of chessplayers, past and present written by Arpad Elo (Elo, 1978). A relatively simple model, it takes the strength of each competitor and creates an expected probability of the team winning. The probability domain ranges between 0 and 1, and so by extension the competitors probability of winning is \((1 - E_A)\). Elo models can be either adaptive to be used as a season progresses or can be constant based on game results of historical data. The constant Elo method for rating teams uses optimisation methods to minimise errors when predicting results of past matches.

3.1.2 Past Applications

Elo ratings have had a range of applications in sports ratings, with one example being Hvattum, L.M. and Arntzen, H. (2010) applying it to association football (soccer). In their paper they applied a variable Elo rating system that incorporated a home ground advantage. They used this variable Elo rating method in logit regression models, which were then used to place hypothetical bets. After evaluation and benchmarking against other methods, they found the models based on Elo ratings to perform better than all other models. The only exceptions to this were models based on betting market information. Further, they found the variable Elo rating methods to be significant predictors of actual game results, which further solidifies their applications outside of academia.

Ryall, R. and Bedford, A. (2010) also applied optimised Elo ratings models to another sporting code: Australian Rules Football (AFL). Their addition to the model examined home ground advantage of each game, if present. The home ground advantage was incorporated into the Elo prediction model by way of stacking the rating of a home team higher for when they were playing to a home ground advantage. They found adding a home ground advantage did not improve the Elo rating system as compared to previous work by Stefani and Clarke (1992), but cited the low variation in team premiership points as a potentially confounding factor.

3.2 Monte Carlo Simulation

3.2.1 Overview

Monte Carlo simulations are simple in their structure, which lends them to large iteration chains. A random number generator is used to generate a number between a defined interval, usually \((0<x<1)\). This number is then compared to an expected value. If the expected value is binary, say a coin flip, any number lesser than 0.5 is rounded to 0 and any number greater than or equal to 0.5 is rounded to 1. The distribution of the random number generator can also be chosen, and a uniform distribution with equal probability between any given points in the interval is most common. This process is repeated several times to simulate thousands of observations. (Theodore & Prochaska, 2018)

4 Methods

4.1 Data Source

Regular season game schedule and results were taken from Hockey-Reference.com, a subsidiary of Sports Reference LLC. The data contained Date of Game, Visiting (Away) Team, Goals scored by Away Team, Home Team, Goals scored by Home Team, Win Type (Regular, OT, SO), Attendance, and Length of Game for all games by all teams in the regular season. All of the above variables were used in the following analysis, with Attendance and Length of Game not being considered.

4.2 Optimised Elo Ratings

A constant Elo rating method was used in this study. To determine the optimised Elo ratings of each team in the NHL, the below formula was used to estimate the expected results of each game.

\[ E_A = \frac{1}{1+10^{\left(- \left(\frac{\left(Rating_A - Rating_B \right)}{\delta} \right) \right)}} \]

For each given game, the errors were calculated between the Expected result and the actual result of the match. Different ratings for each team were optimised by minimising the sum of the squares of the errors. The only constraints on the optimisation were that the team ratings averaged 1500 so as to allow for \(( \delta = 400 )\).

4.3 Data Partitions

Data was partitioned at three points:

  1. Matches where both teams played no more than 25 games

  2. Matches where both teams played no more than 50 games

  3. No partition, where teams had played the full 82 games of the season

The first partition was based on the ladder position of the St.Louis Blues after that game number; their lowest point in the season and ranked 30 out of total 31 teams in the League.
The second partition was chosen arbitrarily. The rationale was for the partition to be twice as many games as the first partition and approximately 2/3\(^{rds}\) of the regular season.
The last partition, or no partition at all, was chosen to examine the St.Louis Blues chances of winning the Stanley Cup after their final standing in the season.

4.4 Monte Carlo Simulation

4.4.1 Regular Season

During the regular seasons for partitions 25 and 50, games from 26 and 51 onwards (respectively) were simulated using Monte Carlo methods. A uniform distribution between 0 and 1 was used and compared to the expected results. If the expected result, from Team As perspective, was greater than the random number a win was recorded, with the winning team earning 2 points to their standings. If the expected result was lesser than the random number by no more than 5 percent, an overtime loss was recorded for Team A and they were awarded 1 point. If the expected result was more than 5% lesser than the random number, a regular loss was recorded and Team A awarded 0 points to their standings.

\[ Points_{A\ |\ \left(E_A > RNG \right)}=2 \]

\[ Points_{A\ |\ \left(E_A < \left(RNG \times 0.95\right) \right)}=0 \]

\[ Points_{A\ |\ \left(\left(E_A < RNG \right)\ \&\ E_A > \left(RNG \times 0.95 \right) \right)}=1 \]

4.4.2 Finals Playoffs

The above points system using overtime losses was not used in each stage of the finals playoffs as point scoring in each playoffs series is binary; win or loss. The model was simplified to only compare the expected results to the random number, and any expected result greater than the random number was recorded as a win to Team A.

\[ Points_{A\ |\ E_A<RNG}=1 \] \[ Points_B = 1- Points_A \]

The first team to reach 4 wins proceeded to the next round per the finals structure outlined in section 2.2.1 above. This was repeated for each stage in the finals playoffs including the final round, the Stanley Cup playoffs, where the first team to 4 wins was also simulated to be the champion of that iteration in the simulation.

4.4.3 Monte Carlo Simulations on Partitioned Data

4.4.3.1 Partitions 25 and 50

The Monte Carlo simulations were performed on the data partitions at games 25 and 50. All games in the regular season were simulated after the partition using constant Elo ratings from games prior to the partition. That is, games 26 to 82 were simulated using Elo ratings optimised on games 1 to 25, and games 51 to 82 were simulated using Elo ratings optimised on games 1 to 50.

4.4.3.2 No Partition: 82 Games

The final simulation did not simulate matches in the regular season but only simulated games in the post-season playoffs using Elo ratings optimised on match results for games 1 to 82.

  for (j in 1:nrow(Game_Monte_51)) {
    
    Game_Monte_51$RNG[j] <- runif(n = 1, min = 0, max = 1)

                                        Game_Monte_51$Expected[j] <= Game_Monte_51$RNG[j],
                                      true = 1,
                                      false = if_else(Game_Monte_51$Expected[j] > Game_Monte_51$RNG[j],
                                                      true = 2,
                                                      false = 0))

                                        Game_Monte_51$Expected[j] >= Game_Monte_51$RNG[j],

As can be seen, the St.Louis Blues distribution of simulated finishing posisitions changed substantially between the two data partitions at game 25 and game 50. The distribution of finishing positions using partition 25 was left-skewed and with a median of 30 and a mean of 29. The distribution of simulated season finishing positions shifted with the game 50 partition to be centred around a median of 18 and a mean of 17.6. Unlike the game 25 partition, the game 50 partition yielded a more symmetrical distribution of finishing positions.

6 Discussion

6.1 St.Louis Blues

The simulations of the three partitions reflected the marked improvement in the St.Louis Blues performance throughout the season. Using the game 25 partition data, the St.Louis Blues won the Stanley Cup a total of 0 times out of 5 simulations, which was a likelihood of 0.00%. This improved somewhat when comparing to the game 50 partition data, which saw the St Louis Blues win a total of 0 out of 5 simulations (likelihood of 0.00%). The biggest improvement was seen when simulating the playoffs series based on their standings and performance at the end of the 82-game regular season. Using the 82-game non-partitioned data, the St Louis Blues won the Stanley Cup a total of 1 out of a total 5 trials, which was a likelihood of 20.00%.

This improvement throughout the season was as anticipated, otherwise the Blues would not have been able to win the Stanley Cup. What was most interesting, however, was that the St.Louis Blues still managed to win the Stanley Cup despite the simulations using the non-partitioned season data showing their likelihood of winning to be a mere 20.00%

6.2 Other Teams - Noteworthy Results

6.2.1 Boston

Despite their long and repeated history of Stanley Cup playoffs appearances, the Boston Bruins were no more a certainty of making the finals than most other teams. After their 25th game, the simulations showed Boston won the Cup 0 out of 5 simulations, which was a likelihood of 0.00%. This changed a little, but not much in the general context of the competition, when using the 50 game partition. In these simulations Boston took home the Stanley Cup a total of 0 times from 5, which was a likelihood of 0.00%. Of the simulations of non-partitioned data, where the Bruins place in the playoffs was clinched, they won the Stanley Cup 2 out of 5 simulations, a likelihood of 40.00%. Note that this is a slightly greater likelihood of winning the Cup than the St.Louis Blues (20.00%).

6.2.2 Tampa Bay

It could be argued that the Tampa Bay Lightning were robbed of the Stanley Cup this season. In the real data for the season, Tampa Bay performed consistently throughout all fixtures and finished with the most season points, earning them the Presidents Trophy. In the simulations for the game 25 and game 50 partitions, Tampa Bay won the Cup a total of 0 and 3 times, respectively. This equated to a likelihood of 0.00% and 60.00%. This did not change by the end of the season, and the playoffs using the non-partitioned 82 game data saw Tampa Bay winning a total of 0 Stanley Cups, which was a likelihood of 0.00%.

6.2.3 Nashville

Nashville had a very strong start to the season, as shown in the results from the simulations using the 25 game partition. Nashville won a total of 1 times out of 5 simulations, giving a likelihood of 20.00%. This likelihood of winning the Stanley Cup at game 25 was greater than even Tampa Bay. This high performance for Nashville waned as the season progressed. The 50 game partition saw the Nashville Predators win the Stanley Cup a total of 0 times out of 5 simulations, which was a likelihood of just 0.00%. The Predators chances of winning the Stanley Cup increased slightly when using their performance across the whole season in the 82-game non-partition. Here Nashville took home the Cup a total of 0 times from 5, which was a likelihood of 0.00%.

6.3 Limitations

6.3.1 Partitioning

Due to the staggered nature of number of games played across teams, some data was lost when partitioning on game number. For example, if all fixtures from game 25 onwards were filtered out of a data partition, games where Team A were playing their 23rd game and Team B were playing their 26th game were lost; neither considered in the constant Elo rating optimisation nor the partitioned data used to simulate the remaining season. A more effective method for partitioning the data would be based on date coupled with a refining of the season standings scoring method.

6.3.2 Season Standings

The method used for calculating the season standings was too simple for the intended purpose. Points were calculated simply based on whether the team won, lost, or had an overtime loss. This greatly contrasts the season standings scoring method used by the NHL, which is more complex and comprises goals scored differential, games results between tied teams, and season points in the context of number of games played.

6.3.3 Simulated Game Structure

The simulations could have also been improved by incorporating a simulation of points scored, which would have assisted with determining season standings (as outlined above) as well as provided a more realistic simulation of the regular season. Overtime losses were based on the difference between a random number and Elo expected results, which reduced the results of the game to a ternary data structure (0, 1, 2). Using a multiple regression model to simulate goals scored by teams would facilitate adding this level of granularity to the simulations.

6.3.4 Replicating the Stanley Cup Playoffs

Whilst the St.Louis Blues and Boston Bruins were guaranteed spots in the playoffs based on their standings after the regular season ended, the simulations did not deliberately cover this scenario. Granted, the St.Louis Blues and Boston Bruins did meet in the Stanley Cup in the simulations, but they did so purely by the chance of the random number generator. It would be of interest to create further simulations specifically for the Stanley Cup Finals that replicated the team most likely to win between the St.Louis Blues and the Boston Bruins.

6.3.5 Elo Ratings - Recency

Part of the reason why the St.Louis Blues winning the Stanley Cup was so sensational was that they stormed home at the end of the season from rocky beginnings. The Elo ratings used for the simulations based on the non-partitioned 82-game season would have failed to adequately measure the strength of the St.Louis Blues in the finals 30 or so games of the regular season. As such, the Blues may have been underrepresented in these simulations. Creating optimised Elo ratings based on a more recent and similarly sized partition of the data, for example between games 50 and 82, would allow for simulations to be run that reflect the strong performance of the St.Louis Blues in the end of the regular season.

7 Conclusions

This study made some interesting findings, even if they were slightly as anticipated. The change in the St.Louis Blues performance was well reflected in the simulations. The simulations also revealed that, even after the St.Louis Blues chances of making the finals from their standings at the end of their 25th game were approaching nil, the large turn around in their season that was required to make the playoffs still meant that their likelihood of winning the Stanley Cup was low compared to their competitors.

The Boston Bruins were shown to have similar, but slightly greater, likelihood of winning the Stanley Cup than the St.Louis Blues when using Elo ratings from the entire season. At the two other partitions considered, at games 25 and 50, the Boston Bruins had a substantially greater likelihood of winning the Stanley Cup. Further simulations were justified that specifically simulated the playoffs between the Boston Bruins and the St.Louis Blues.
